Certainly, Jack! If you have eight different sized panels and you want to specify the dimensions for each one individually, you can modify your CSS to accommodate these specific sizes. Here's an updated example with individually specified dimensions for each panel:

1. HTML Structure (No changes from the previous example):
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
    <title>Comic Book Panels</title>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="comic-panel panel1">
        <img src="panel1.jpg" alt="Panel 1">
    </div>
    <div class="comic-panel panel2">
        <img src="panel2.jpg" alt="Panel 2">
    </div>
    <!-- Add more panels as needed -->
</body>
</html>
```

2. CSS Styles (styles.css):
   Now, we'll specify individual dimensions for each panel using CSS classes based on your image names (e.g., `panel1`, `panel2`, etc.).

```css
/* Reset default margin and padding */
body, html {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
}

/* Define styles for Panel 1 */
.panel1 {
    width: 300px;
    height: 400px;
    margin: 10px;
}

/* Define styles for Panel 2 */
.panel2 {
    width: 250px;
    height: 350px;
    margin: 10px;
}

/* Add styles for other panels (panel3, panel4, etc.) as needed */
```

3. Explanation:
   - We assign a unique class to each `<div>` element based on the image it contains (e.g., `panel1`, `panel2`).
   - For each class, you can specify the width, height, and margin individually according to the dimensions of the corresponding image.

4. Logging (No changes from the previous example):
   You can still use the same logging code as before to log messages in JavaScript.

Remember to repeat the process for each panel, creating a CSS class and specifying dimensions for each one individually. This way, you can have full control over the sizes and positions of your comic book panels.

