Yes, you can use the `position: relative;` CSS property in combination with the `left`, `right`, `top`, and `bottom` properties to set your panels in various locations on the web page. However, using `position: relative;` alone won't directly position the panels in different locations. It's more about how elements inside the panel are positioned relative to the panel itself.

Here's how you can achieve positioning of panels with `position: relative;`:

1. HTML Structure (Same as previous example):
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
    <title>Comic Book Panels</title>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="comic-panel panel1">
        <img src="panel1.jpg" alt="Panel 1">
    </div>
    <div class="comic-panel panel2">
        <img src="panel2.jpg" alt="Panel 2">
    </div>
    <!-- Add more panels as needed -->
</body>
</html>
```

2. CSS Styles (styles.css):
   To position the panels differently, you can use `position: relative;` in combination with `left`, `right`, `top`, and `bottom`. Here's an example of positioning Panel 1 to the top-left corner:

```css
/* Define styles for Panel 1 */
.panel1 {
    width: 300px;
    height: 400px;
    margin: 10px;
    position: relative;
    left: 0;
    top: 0;
}
```

- The `position: relative;` property is applied to the panel element.
- `left: 0;` and `top: 0;` set Panel 1 to the top-left corner of its parent container.

You can adjust the `left` and `top` values to position each panel as desired. For example, to position Panel 2 to the top-right corner, you can use:

```css
/* Define styles for Panel 2 */
.panel2 {
    width: 300px;
    height: 400px;
    margin: 10px;
    position: relative;
    right: 0;
    top: 0;
}
```

Repeat this process for each panel, adjusting the `left` and `top` (or `right` and `top`) values to position them where you want on the page.

Remember that the positions are relative to the container of the panel, so ensure that the container has the appropriate dimensions and positioning if needed.

